Time-series forecasting

 needs(rmarkdown)

A walk-through of model selection for univariate time-series analysis

In 2017, The New York Times did something unusual. They predicted how many people would die from drug overdoses in 2016 before the CDC released the official data. They did so with a mix of reporting and forecasting: Esimating future trends based on past data.

I know from speaking to the reporter at the Times who did the analysis how they did their forecast: They had so much data reported ahead of time, they just averaged what they just took the average increase in overdoses from the data they had and extrapolated to the places where data was missing.

Here, I take a different tact. I just use the Forecast package in R to generate predictions for 2018 based on half a years data. The CDC has released data through July, 2018. Well forecast to January.

Next, well fit a few simple models from Forecast: a random walk, drift and naive seasonal model. We fit them on the data up to January, 2018, because that includes the 2018 spike. We test against the first six months of 2018 because the curve seems to reverse there, and a good model would not be pulled too far by 2017.

They dont seem to fit very well. We crossvalidate our models and look at the RMSE, MAE, MPE, MAPE, MASE on our training and test sets to gauge fit. None are fitting all that well (though the naive model fits best). We at least have a baseline from which to gauge other models. Well move on to trying som eothers.

  pre18fit1 <- meanf(dfPreUStsto18)
  pre18fit2 <- naive(dfPreUStsto18)
  pre18fit3 <- snaive(dfPreUStsto18)
  pre18fit4 <- rwf(dfPreUStsto18, drift=TRUE)

Next, well look at ETS and ARIMA models. We see the ARIMA model does quite well. We use auto.arima to stepwise select the best combinations of p and q for the model.

  # Takes 10 mins to run
  fets <- function(x, h) { stlf(x,method="ets",h=h)}
  farima <- function(x, h) { forecast(auto.arima(x), h=h) }
  
  e9 <- tsCV(dfPreUSts, farima)
  e10 <- tsCV(dfPreUSts, fets)
  
  sqrt(mean(e9^2, na.rm=TRUE))

Likewise, splines and exponentials dont do so well for us. We need to capture the recent trend rather than trend over the entire series, which is why the ARIMA did so well.

  fit.exp <- tslm(dfPreUStsto18 ~ trend + season, lambda = 0)

Finally, we choose the auto.arima as our best model from Forecast. We bootstrap and aggregate (bag) our predictions to produce a confidence interval for our predictions. The trend line for 2018 drug overdoses we arrive at is seen below. According to our model, they continued to increase in 2018.

  # bagged forecast with auto.arima
  # https://otexts.com/fpp2/bootstrap.html
  # takes 20 min to run
  
  start <- tsp(dfPreUSts)[2]+1/12

  sim <- bld.mbb.bootstrap(dfPreUSts, 100) %>%
            as.data.frame() %>%
            ts(frequency=12, start=c(1999,1))

  fc <- purrr::map(as.list(sim),
             function(x){forecast(auto.arima(x), h=6)[["mean"]]}) %>%
        as.data.frame() %>%
        ts(frequency=12, start=start)
  
  autoplot(dfPreUSts, ylim=c(0,8000), series="Observed data") +
    autolayer(fc, series="Forecast data", alpha=0.25) +
    autolayer(dfPreUSts, series="Observed data", colour=FALSE) +
    ylab("Drug overdose deaths")  +
    guides(colour="none")

A future exploration might try fitting models in Stan instead of the Forecast package.
